pe.&nbsp;</span></p>','<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Building codes and regulations are constantly changing and evolving in an attempt to ensure that all new construction projects are implementing the safest and most effective systems. Due to this volatility of the minimum requirements for buildings, it can be quite tricky at times to design an entire project before an amendment to the building codes. It is not entirely uncommon for the designer of a building to plan to surpass requirements detailed in the building codes in order to compensate for future changes.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">&nbsp;When faced with an issue regarding changes to a plan that are necessary due to more stringent codes it is often quite difficult to resolve these issues without creating additional costs or potential delays to the project&rsquo;s overall schedule. In order to avoid or mitigate these negative consequences, adjustments can be made to ownership of portions of the project&rsquo;s scope in regards to the subcontractors who are to complete this work. By doing such, one may be able to minimize the cost for adding additional work to the original scope.&nbsp;</span></p>','2016-04-11 16:44:50','2016-04-11 16:44:50'),(63,'App\\Study',7,1,'excerpt','&nbsp;\r\nOn a recent high-rise, class &lsquo;A&rsquo;, office tower, the controls subcontractor was awarded a contract that included the integration of the building\'s fire alarm control panel and the respective life-safety systems. Due to recent code changes and the fact that the fire alarm system was a newer generation; the system required more detailed controls. As a result, many questions and concerns arose....','On a recent high-rise, class &lsquo;A&rsquo;, office tower, the controls subcontractor was awarded a contract that included the integration of the building\'s fire alarm control panel and the respective life-safety systems. Due to recent code changes and the fact that the fire alarm system was a 