ct to compliance with an Order of Conditions, which we are following.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">A local resident and activist had decided that the project parking lots should be drained using pervious pavement in lieu of standard impervious pavement, regardless of the intent of the aforementioned design to mitigate high storm water runoff.&nbsp; A lawsuit was filed by the resident, and the hospital eventually agreed to install the pervious pavement in order to avoid financial risk and to move the project forward.&nbsp; This circumstance added two months of indecision and delay to the project construction, and added a substantial premium to the budget for the pervious pavement cost.&nbsp; Work had to be rescheduled out of normal sequence, and the total project duration increased as a result of accommodating this change.</span></p>','<p>Using previously agreed upon schedules, we demonstrated to the Owner that they needed to make an early decision to avoid delays, but due to legal review, they were not able to do so.&nbsp; We had to reschedule the landscaping work to be done before the subgrade stone and gravel layers were installed under the pavement to avoid \"contamination\" and clogging of eventual water pathways.&nbsp; This had to be carefully orchestrated with other site work activities (site lighting and conduits, drain and sanitary sewer work and curb installation) that were ongoing.&nbsp; We have had to expend significant premium time, working evenings and weekends, to try and maintain our completion date.</p>','<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The largest issue that is seen in this scenario is actually out of the contractor\'s power to directly fix. The resident/ activist who chose to file a lawsuit against the owner is creating a scheduling problem. This case is interesting, however, because the resident was not in the wrong for attempting to create a more efficient landscape for the community, that individual just wanted what was best for the project. Perhaps the wrong methods, but nevertheless. If the owner or architect truly wanted the impervious pavement for a project located on a flood plain, it can be argued that they may have overlooked a drainage factor during the design stages of the project. Or perhaps the impervious pavement had other qualities, such as high workability, superior durability, extreme strength, or just a familiar product that the designers knew worked well. These are factors unknown to the author, but important to think about. What the contractor could have done is this; review the project a little more in depth. Had the contractor noted the discrepancy between location and material choice, chosen to investigate a little deeper, and started a dialogue with the owner, for example:</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">&nbsp;\"Are there any other alternates to this impervious pavement? If proper drainage is crucial to this project shouldn\'t we look into a more suitable material?\"&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">There is a possibility that this matter could have been avoided all together. The owner would have impressed, as well as appreciative of the fact that the contractor cared enough about the project to attempt to make it more successful.</span>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">As a result of the lawsuit, the material order, and the change order, the schedule was delayed by two months. The contractor had to work late nights and weekends, but he/ she provided a solution that was a win-win for all parties involved. Multiple subcontractors were pulled onto the job site during construction to work around the issue. The scheduled was delayed and some work had to be completed in not ideal situations, but the work was completed satisfactorily. The owner, contractor, activist, and the environment are all pleased.</span></p>','We are performing a project for a hospital, and the project is located on a flood plain.&nbsp; The Civil/Site Engineer incorporated massive underground surge tanks and infiltration champers in the design to capture water from heavy rains and snow melts, and subsequently disperse the water slowly back to the watershed in order to mitigate against the flooding that occurs during these events.&nbsp; The town Conservation Commission has reviewed and approved the project design subject to compliance ...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-1-untitled',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 15:58:51','2016-04-11 16:01:11'),(3,'Case 2','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">While performing a pre-trench excavation for a slurry wall foundation, which is a technique used to build reinforced concrete walls in areas of soft earth, our team encountered soil which showed evidence of a petroleum leak from a previously unknown underground storage tank.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">There was no feasible alternative to keep work going and productivity up, so work was stopped. The Licensed Site Professional was contacted to begin soil and storage tank removal and remediation. Schedule and project budget were impacted negatively.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">While the problem yields a solution that does not necessarily leave room for salvaging time and money, it does show the potential for things to go wrong when the work - in this case specifically, site surveying- is not 100% complete and accurate. Which in construction, is almost common tradition. Along those lines, it is never a good thing for there to be a show-stopping event, but that does not mean that all is lost and the project will run over budget and over schedule. Potential mistakes and setbacks are typically accounted for during the estimating process. A construction manager\'s quick, effective, and positive response and attitude towards any given problematic situation is just as crucial to the project as is the situation itself. Being a responsible construction entity will ensure that the other parties of the contract, the owners, the subcontractors, and the advising companies, that their work, money, and time is in the hands of the right individual. This results not only in a favorable reputation for the future, but also compliance with future requests.</span></p>','&nbsp;\r\nWhile performing a pre-trench excavation for a slurry wall foundation, which is a technique used to build reinforced concrete walls in areas of soft earth, our team encountered soil which showed evidence of a petroleum leak from a previously unknown underground storage tank....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-2',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 16:00:49','2016-04-11 16:00:49'),(4,'Case 3','<p>&nbsp;<span class=\"s1\">We had limited room for mobilizing our workforce on a tight construction site in Boston.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;<span class=\"s1\">We had the structural engineer redesign the steel at street level in order to accommodate the truck loading. This allowed us to use the street level for the truss erection of granite panels in the atrium, concrete placement at the loading dock, and truck deliveries, for items such as spray fireproofing.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;<span class=\"s1\">This scenario is perhaps one of the most common issues associated with modern, urban, construction projects. Even the simplest of buildings can become a logistical nightmare when there is a lack of space to mobilize the project. When one is faced with an issue such as this, it can prove to be quite costly in terms of time and money if the situation is not dealt with in the appropriate fashion. This case is a perfect example of how one might overcome the limitations set by a congested jobsite. Not every issue can be solved by the construction manager alone. More often than not, the CM will find it beneficial to consult their subcontractor, design team, and even owners in regards to more specialized issues. In this particular instance, the mobilization was significantly facilitated as a result of assistance from the project&rsquo;s structural subcontractor.&nbsp;</span></p>','&nbsp;We had limited room for mobilizing our workforce on a tight construction site in Boston....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-3',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 16:02:24','2016-04-11 16:02:41'),(5,'Case 4','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We were managing a build out of a graduate dormitory with three floors of underground parking.&nbsp; Upon reaching the bottom of the excavation, we encountered a tremendous amount of rainfall within a two to three day period. On Friday, everyone left the site ready to pour the concrete crane pad on the following Monday.&nbsp; However, after several days of rain, the six foot tall concrete forms were buried along with the &lsquo;balance of the excavation&rsquo; which measured approximately 100\' x 50\'. It was an extremely dangerous situation and to make matters worse, the pumps that we had been using for dewatering, were shut down by the city and state so that they could try and get ahead of flood situations in other areas.&nbsp;</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Since the site was underwater and we were at the mercy of the city officials, the site was effectively shut down.&nbsp; We kept essential personnel on site and worked with city officials in order to figure out where we could pump our water to. Ultimately, we were allowed to pump though our sediment tanks and divert the water into a nearby river. Despite the fact that the river was running high, we were allowed to continue seeing as there were officials monitoring the flow of the river. Our efforts with filters and sediment tank were not perfect; plumes would emerge in the river occasionally. Once we were allowed to pump, we monitored the site for 24 hours and within approximately two days; we were back up and running.</span></p>','<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">One of the hardest factors to take into consideration when planning a project is the influence that the weather/environment will have on the safety and feasibility of the project. While it is possible for one to look at historical weather data in an attempt to predict the occurrence of adverse weather, there is no way for anyone to estimate the exact time or day these events may take place.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">&nbsp;If and when a construction manager encounters a situation where a natural event causes an unavoidable delay, it is absolutely crucial that they maintain a calm and collected approach to resolving the issue at hand. Once they have had the opportunity to properly access the situation, the construction manager can and should address all of the involved parties in order to produce the most effective solution to the delay.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">&nbsp;By taking this calm and collected approach to the situation, the construction manager will develop an effective solution to the delay while also building upon their credibility with the owner, subcontractors, and anyone else involved.</span></p>','&nbsp;\r\nWe were managing a build out of a graduate dormitory with three floors of underground parking.&nbsp; Upon reaching the bottom of the excavation, we encountered a tremendous amount of rainfall within a two to three day period. On Friday, everyone left the site ready to pour the concrete crane pad on the following Monday.&nbsp; However, after several days of rain, the six foot tall concrete forms were buried along with the &lsquo;balance of the excavation&rsquo; which measured approximatel...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-4',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 16:03:48','2016-04-11 16:03:48'),(6,'Case 5','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We had a significantly sized area of exposed cast-in-place concrete that was supposed to have an \'architectural\' finish on it. However, the end product did NOT turn out the way that either the owner or architect had designed it to look.&nbsp; Consequentially, the architect refused to sign off on the work completed and the owner even refused to pay for the subpar product.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We held multiple meetings on worksite with the concrete subcontractor, owner, and architect in order to determine a suitable alternative to the work that was incorrectly completed. We got a quote from a concrete finishing and staining company to resolve the issue by using a specialized product. At the same time, we let the concrete subcontractor work on what they believed to be the correct solution. The price of the alternative recommended by the architect and the threat of a backcharge convinced the concrete subcontractor to utilize their best finishers. Ultimately, they ended up spending less than they could have and the owner and architect were satisfied with both our efforts to correct the problem and the subcontractor&rsquo;s efforts to resolve the issue at hand.</span></p>','<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">As a construction manager on a jobsite, it is of upmost importance that one ensures that the work being completed by the contractors and subcontractors meets the standards that are set by the owner and the architect/engineer. In an ideal world, the work completed would always conform to the expectations of the owner. However, there is always the possibility for the exact opposite to occur and for disputes to develop between the involved parties.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">When faced with the issue of subpar quality of work completed, it can be quite difficult to resolve the associated issues regarding additional costs and scheduling delays. It is important to consult the project&rsquo;s design plans and specifications in order to determine who is responsible for the excess costs and delays. At the same time, the construction manager should be coordinating with the owner and architect to develop a plan to resolve any issues that are remaining.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Through this conflict resolution process, it is possible that the owner realizes that the cost for correcting the errors prove to be greater than the value of the error.</span></p>','&nbsp;\r\nWe had a significantly sized area of exposed cast-in-place concrete that was supposed to have an \'architectural\' finish on it. However, the end product did NOT turn out the way that either the owner or architect had designed it to look.&nbsp; Consequentially, the architect refused to sign off on the work completed and the owner even refused to pay for the subpar product....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-5',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 16:04:50','2016-04-11 16:04:50'),(7,'Case 6','<p>On a recent high-rise, class &lsquo;A&rsquo;, office tower, the controls subcontractor was awarded a contract that included the integration of the building\'s fire alarm control panel and the respective life-safety systems. Due to recent code changes and the fact that the fire alarm system was a newer generation; the system required more detailed controls. As a result, many questions and concerns arose.</p>','<p><span class=\"s1\">The complete system was studied and eventually broken down in order to revise the scope. Once broke down, the controls subcontractor helped to determine which items would remain in their scope of work while the remainders were transferred to the fire alarm subcontractor&rsquo;s scope. Ultimately, the majority of the controls integration for the fire alarm system was completed by the fire alarm contractor.</span></p>','<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Building codes and regulations are constantly changing and evolving in an attempt to ensure that all new construction projects are implementing the safest and most effective systems. Due to this volatility of the minimum requirements for buildings, it can be quite tricky at times to design an entire project before an amendment to the building codes. It is not entirely uncommon for the designer of a building to plan to surpass requirements detailed in the building codes in order to compensate for future changes.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">&nbsp;When faced with an issue regarding changes to a plan that are necessary due to more stringent codes it is often quite difficult to resolve these issues without creating additional costs or potential delays to the project&rsquo;s overall schedule. In order to avoid or mitigate these negative consequences, adjustments can be made to ownership of portions of the project&rsquo;s scope in regards to the subcontractors who are to complete this work. By doing such, one may be able to minimize the cost for adding additional work to the original scope.&nbsp;</span></p>','On a recent high-rise, class &lsquo;A&rsquo;, office tower, the controls subcontractor was awarded a contract that included the integration of the building\'s fire alarm control panel and the respective life-safety systems. Due to recent code changes and the fact that the fire alarm system was a newer generation; the system required more detailed controls. As a result, many questions and concerns arose....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-6',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 16:05:50','2016-04-11 16:44:50'),(8,'Case 7','<p><span class=\"s1\">A project we were working on involved the erection of a 5-story precast garage on top of a cast-in-place foundation. About 3 stories into the erection, we noticed some cracks one of the foundation piers in the center of the garage. Upon investigation of the pier, it was determined that several stirrups were located in the wrong place. The project was already delayed due to a tough winter and had to be completed on time so as to avoid incurring any penalties.</span></p>','<p><span class=\"s1\">In order to avoid delaying the project while the problem was addressed, we worked with a reshore designer, precast designer, and the original structural engineer to design a system to shore the building while continuing the precast erection and the removal and replacement of the missing rebar stirrups. An additional work crew was required to remove and replace the pier without delaying the original construction team beyond the investigation delay and in due course, meet the project&rsquo;s deadline.</span></p>','','A project we were working on involved the erection of a 5-story precast garage on top of a cast-in-place foundation. About 3 stories into the erection, we noticed some cracks one of the foundation piers in the center of the garage. Upon investigation of the pier, it was determined that several stirrups were located in the wrong place. The project was already delayed due to a tough winter and had to be completed on time so as to avoid incurring any penalties....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-7',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 16:08:32','2016-04-11 16:44:32'),(9,'Case 8','<p><span class=\"s1\">The company for which I work for was awarded 13 projects for which we hired additional employees and also accounted for within our financial projections. Numerous weeks after the award, the client decided to withdraw 10 of the projects. This decision left us with just 3 projects in addition to a surplus of employees that we would have to reallocate in addition to significant financial implications.</span></p>','<p><span class=\"s1\">We responded to the issue by reallocating the staff to other assignments in different roles that were within their skill sets for the time being. Our business cycle, business development efforts, growth, and backlog indicated that the projects we had lost would soon be replaced with projects from new clients. With these new opportunities, we would be able to continue our normal operations.</span></p>','','The company for which I work for was awarded 13 projects for which we hired additional employees and also accounted for within our financial projections. Numerous weeks after the award, the client decided to withdraw 10 of the projects. This decision left us with just 3 projects in addition to a surplus of employees that we would have to reallocate in addition to significant financial implications....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-8',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 16:09:43','2016-04-11 16:44:15'),(10,'Case 9','<p><span class=\"s1\">We were awarded a contract to provide construction management services to a University working on an existing building. The work was to be performed on the 4th floor with classrooms and research labs below. The schedule for work is from January to June which meant the building was fully functional. The scope of work included the full &lsquo;fitout&rsquo; of labs, offices, and bathrooms. The majority of the utility work for the project required a tie-in to the floor below, inside of classrooms and research labs.</span></p>','<p><span class=\"s1\">We obtained a schedule of the classes that were to be held on the floors below and scheduled our work around the classroom times in order to limit the noise hear from the floor below. We also scheduled all of the 3rd floor utility tie-in work to occur during the break periods to limit disturbances.</span></p>','','We were awarded a contract to provide construction management services to a University working on an existing building. The work was to be performed on the 4th floor with classrooms and research labs below. The schedule for work is from January to June which meant the building was fully functional. The scope of work included the full &lsquo;fitout&rsquo; of labs, offices, and bathrooms. The majority of the utility work for the project required a tie-in to the floor below, inside of classrooms an...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-9',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 16:10:51','2016-04-11 16:44:00'),(11,'Case 10','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">You are awarded a project under a CM at Risk Contract that was estimated based upon incomplete drawings. The project has been completely bought out and all of the subcontractors have been selected. During the shop drawing process, it becomes apparent that the respective shop drawing detailers from each subcontractor (concrete reinforcement, structural steel, curtain walls) need to assume and complete extra design work in order to make up for the incomplete drawings. Consequentially, the subcontractors want to send a back charge for the extra work that was incurred and they all have legal documentation that would allow them to do so. These back charges would exceed your GMP for the project and is harming your schedule by the day.</span></p>','<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We, as the construction management team, maintained careful documentation of all of the extra design work required for the subcontractors. In order to facilitate the opportunity to design based on the shop drawings as we proceeded we scheduled weekly meetings with the design team and sub-contractors. Although it took extra time from our subcontractors and our staff, we were able to resolve the design issues as they arose; rather than deal with the constant process of revising and re-submitting drawings which would have led to even more costs.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We also had the extra documentation to prove where extra compensation was needed, had our meetings not been productive.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nYou are awarded a project under a CM at Risk Contract that was estimated based upon incomplete drawings. The project has been completely bought out and all of the subcontractors have been selected. During the shop drawing process, it becomes apparent that the respective shop drawing detailers from each subcontractor (concrete reinforcement, structural steel, curtain walls) need to assume and complete extra design work in order to make up for the incomplete drawings. Consequentially, the ...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-10',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 16:12:16','2016-04-11 16:43:33'),(12,'Case 11','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We bought-out the \"Site Improvements\" (sidewalks, hardscapes, landscaping, etc.) bid package from a trade contractor. In return, this contractor subbed out the landscaping portion of the package to a landscaping subcontractor. After about half of the landscape work was complete, the landscape subcontractor notified us that they were not receiving payment from the Site Improvements trade contractor, despite the fact that the Site Improvements trade contractor had been paid by the Construction Manager. The Landscape subcontractor threatened to withdraw their crew from the job until payment was received in-full.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">During the following month\'s payment requisition (and every month thereafter), we paid the Site Improvements trade contractor via \"Joint Check\" in order to ensure that the appropriate amount of payment was being transferred directly to the Landscape subcontractor.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nWe bought-out the \"Site Improvements\" (sidewalks, hardscapes, landscaping, etc.) bid package from a trade contractor. In return, this contractor subbed out the landscaping portion of the package to a landscaping subcontractor. After about half of the landscape work was complete, the landscape subcontractor notified us that they were not receiving payment from the Site Improvements trade contractor, despite the fact that the Site Improvements trade contractor had been paid by the Construc...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-11',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:22:11','2016-04-11 17:22:11'),(13,'Case 12','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">In these tough economic times, one of our trade contractors was not paying his subcontractors. This caused his subcontractors to threaten to not supply materials or workers to the job. If this were to happen, it would cause a delay in the job that we could not afford.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Our company has a joint check process in which pay the subcontractors with the money we held on the original subcontractor with a joint check that is signed by both parties.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nIn these tough economic times, one of our trade contractors was not paying his subcontractors. This caused his subcontractors to threaten to not supply materials or workers to the job. If this were to happen, it would cause a delay in the job that we could not afford....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-12',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:23:07','2016-04-11 17:23:07'),(14,'Case 13','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We were the low bidder on a DCAM project. The bid was protested based on the claim that the subcontractors did not prequalify using the same standards that were required for the file sub bidder.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We met with the Attorney General and ultimately DCAM and the AG agreed with our position that sub bidders did not need to prequalify.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nWe were the low bidder on a DCAM project. The bid was protested based on the claim that the subcontractors did not prequalify using the same standards that were required for the file sub bidder....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-13',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:23:53','2016-04-11 17:23:53'),(15,'Case 14','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The company I work for was awarded a job at a private university that was bid to start in May. After the project was awarded, the university advisory board opted to put the project on hold due to funding concerns. A few months later, we were given the go ahead to begin construction in late August. The budget for the project was based on the concrete and structural steel work being completed before winter; with a start date of late August this was no longer feasible. The original GMP proposal did not include costs for this work being done through the winter.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">After many meeting with the owners, and design team, there was a financial agreement reached for winter conditions as well as mixing additives into the concrete along with a complete change to the soil management plan. The overall duration of the project was not affected by these changes.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nThe company I work for was awarded a job at a private university that was bid to start in May. After the project was awarded, the university advisory board opted to put the project on hold due to funding concerns. A few months later, we were given the go ahead to begin construction in late August. The budget for the project was based on the concrete and structural steel work being completed before winter; with a start date of late August this was no longer feasible. The original GMP prop...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-14',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:25:09','2016-04-11 17:25:09'),(16,'Case 15','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">A project I was managing at University required the replacement of the existing windows and storefronts of a building on campus. The project was ahead of schedule and we were on track to receive an early job completion savings from the owner. Unfortunately, Hurricane Irene hit the states hard and our storefront manufacture had their factory flooded. Due to the flood, the project was delayed for up to 6 months. We took action and found a new storefront manufacturer and we were ultimately able to reduce the previous six month delay, down to a three month delay.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We switched store-front vendors in order to reduce the severity of the delay on the project&rsquo;s scheduled completion.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nA project I was managing at University required the replacement of the existing windows and storefronts of a building on campus. The project was ahead of schedule and we were on track to receive an early job completion savings from the owner. Unfortunately, Hurricane Irene hit the states hard and our storefront manufacture had their factory flooded. Due to the flood, the project was delayed for up to 6 months. We took action and found a new storefront manufacturer and we were ultimately ...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-15',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:25:55','2016-04-11 17:25:55'),(17,'Case 16','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We signed a contract to partially demolish a 100 year old high school. The contract detailed that we would have to preserve the existing masonry facade and incorporate it into the new construction of a 150,000 square foot Data Center.&nbsp; The design documents that we bid the demolition work off of indicated that the wall system consisted of several wythes thick of brick in a solid configuration. After being awarded the contract and beginning the demolition work, we discovered that the wall system had a 2-3 inch cavity. Additionally, the ties from the inside wythes to the exterior wythes mostly consisted of broken bricks. The mortar joints were in worse condition than indicated in the design documents that were provided. The structural properties and behavior of the existing facade were determined, by the structural engineer, to be different than what they had previously assumed. In turn, this impacted their design for the new construction and how it would incorporate the existing facade. The issue required further study and analysis which forced us to stop our work.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We conducted extensive exploratory work of the existing masonry facade (which should have been done by the designer before they started designing) and tested parts of the existing masonry system (brick compression, mortar composition, etc.).&nbsp; The project team (Owner, Architect, Engineer, and Construction Manager) held numerous meetings in order to review the information and discuss the different approaches to solve the issue at hand.&nbsp; Eventually, the structural engineer recommended that we install 5,000 &frac34; inch by 24 inch Hilti masonry anchors with 2-part adhesive and 4 inch reinforced masonry block for back up in order to make the existing facade more secure.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nWe signed a contract to partially demolish a 100 year old high school. The contract detailed that we would have to preserve the existing masonry facade and incorporate it into the new construction of a 150,000 square foot Data Center.&nbsp; The design documents that we bid the demolition work off of indicated that the wall system consisted of several wythes thick of brick in a solid configuration. After being awarded the contract and beginning the demolition work, we discovered that the ...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-16',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:26:56','2016-04-11 17:26:56'),(18,'Case 17','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The company I work for was awarded a project to work on a school and was to be completed over the course of a single summer.&nbsp; Typically, these types of projects are fast paced in nature and consequentially, months of detailed planning by a project team are necessary seeing as nearly every activity is considered to be on the critical path of the schedule. Project superintendents are especially important for these projects, particularly those who take the time to get to know the entire job. Specifically, it proves to be largely beneficial for the superintendent to determine where the risks are and to even create a sequenced plan regarding the execution of the work. The last thing you want to have is a superintendent who does not know the job or who joins the project team late. When the project&rsquo;s buyout was completed and the summer work was about to begin, the project superintendent, who planned out the entire job personally, resigned from the company.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The company immediately brought in a replacement superintendent whose resume indicated that they had previously worked a number of fast paced school projects. Due to the fact that he lived approximately 2 hours away from the jobsite, I, as an intern, took charge for much of the weekend and after hours work. For the first month on the job, I worked side by side with the new superintendent for approximately 70 hours per week. We held daily meetings with key foreman in order to determine where work was available. Additionally, it proved to be important for all of us to keep the communication lines open. The job became a living, breathing creature, with changes and decisions made as they became relevant, rather than the meticulous plan that had been laid out by the previous superintendent. Through effective communication and more than a few double shifts, the school opened on time and we maintained our budget, turning over a profitable project.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nThe company I work for was awarded a project to work on a school and was to be completed over the course of a single summer.&nbsp; Typically, these types of projects are fast paced in nature and consequentially, months of detailed planning by a project team are necessary seeing as nearly every activity is considered to be on the critical path of the schedule. Project superintendents are especially important for these projects, particularly those who take the time to get to know the entir...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-17',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:27:57','2016-04-11 17:27:57'),(19,'Case 18','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We were awarded a project to build a surgery center for a client located in Connecticut. The project was progressing well and we were on schedule and on budget. About 65% into the job, we noticed that the plumbing/HVAC contractor was missing some of their milestone dates and we were receiving calls from the lower tier subcontractors that they were not getting paid in a timely manner.</span></p>','<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">I decided to schedule special focus meetings with the on-site foreman and a key decision maker within the company who in this case, was the Owner. We told them that they had been falling behind lately and we wanted to work closely with them to get the project back on track. We also told them that if things did not improve over the next 2-3 weeks, we would look into utilizing the options available to us in the terms and conditions of our contract. We then set up &ldquo;micro schedules&rdquo; for them to follow and constantly documented their progress or lack of progress as the case may be. Once it became clear that the contractor could not meet their contractual obligations, we contacted the bonding agency and ultimately, had the contractor replaced.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We were able to have this done due to the fact that when we first noticed that there was a potential issue; we immediately notified the contractor and issued a formal letter that described the issue in detail. Next, we followed up with one-on-one focus meetings to address schedule and sequence moves. We provided detailed meeting minutes and status updates that were relative to the scheduling commitments that they agreed upon during the focus meetings. As a result, when we decided to get the bonding agency involved, we were in a perfect position seeing as we had detailed documents that served to explain the contractor&rsquo;s failure to maintain the schedule. In addition, the videos and photos that we had taken so as to record the actual work completed prior to each meeting proved to be invaluable in the replacement process. Once the bonding agency reviewed our detailed information, they had no choice but to pay for the removal of this contractor and all of the costs associated with accelerating the schedule to compensate for the delays.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The lesson here, is that as a Construction Manager, we first need to attempt to help the contractor through their issues. As this is being done, it is crucial to constantly document as much as possible in as high a detail feasible. This documentation should be given to the contractor so they are aware of what you are doing. If the issues are still not resolved after this you will be able to rest easy since you will be in a perfect position to have them replaced without it costing your company any additional expenses through the consultation of the bonding agency. If we had not done our due diligence, it would have cost us a great deal of time and money. Not to mention the fact the Owner would lose their confidence in our ability to meet the predetermined schedule(s).</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nWe were awarded a project to build a surgery center for a client located in Connecticut. The project was progressing well and we were on schedule and on budget. About 65% into the job, we noticed that the plumbing/HVAC contractor was missing some of their milestone dates and we were receiving calls from the lower tier subcontractors that they were not getting paid in a timely manner....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-18',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:29:00','2016-04-11 17:29:00'),(20,'Case 19','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The company that I work for was awarded a GMP contract to conduct an 8 week \"summer slammer\" renovation. Two weeks into the project, we discovered that the existing slab would not be able to withstand the intended load of the new structure.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We tested the existing slab in order to determine the structural capabilities (specifically the PSI strength). The design architect determined that a new structural slab needed to be placed in the common corridor space while the existing slab would prove sufficient for the other spaces.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nThe company that I work for was awarded a GMP contract to conduct an 8 week \"summer slammer\" renovation. Two weeks into the project, we discovered that the existing slab would not be able to withstand the intended load of the new structure....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-19',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:30:06','2016-04-11 17:30:06'),(21,'Case 20','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The Department of Labor recorded the drawings and writings in the porta-johns as a violation of the employee\'s workplace environment.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We sent notification to each trade that was on the work site detailing the nature of these violations. Additionally, we promptly removed all of drawings in the porta-johns and met with all of the employees on the work site in order to review policy with them. Going forward, we informed the workers that anyone found writing in the porta-john would be permanently removed from the site.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nThe Department of Labor recorded the drawings and writings in the porta-johns as a violation of the employee\'s workplace environment....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-20',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:31:19','2016-04-11 17:31:19'),(22,'Case 21','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The soils report for a project did not indicate high levels of underground water. However, when we started digging for pole foundations, we ran into problems with underground water which required additional concrete work.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">In order to come up with a solution, we had extra testing done. Based upon these tests, a recommendation was made to add flowable fill in these locations.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nThe soils report for a project did not indicate high levels of underground water. However, when we started digging for pole foundations, we ran into problems with underground water which required additional concrete work....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-21',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:33:05','2016-04-11 17:33:05'),(23,'Case 22','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">A client recently authorized us to mobilize onto a site while they continued to secure the necessary financing. The site staff subcontracted the job, performed submittal reviews, etc. These services were paid for on a monthly basis.&nbsp; After 12 months of service, the financial institute declined the owner&rsquo;s loan for construction.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Once we received notification, we immediately met with the client to review the current financial situation. This allowed us to regroup internally and in turn, we had to shut the jobsite down in order to minimize costs to the client.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nA client recently authorized us to mobilize onto a site while they continued to secure the necessary financing. The site staff subcontracted the job, performed submittal reviews, etc. These services were paid for on a monthly basis.&nbsp; After 12 months of service, the financial institute declined the owner&rsquo;s loan for construction....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-22',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:33:56','2016-04-11 17:33:56'),(24,'Case 23','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The project our company was working on was impacted by a significant amount of rainfall while the building&rsquo;s foundation and underground construction were beginning. Due to the terms of the contract, all weather delays were excusable but non-compensable. This placed a significant financial burden on the entire project team with regards to extending the general conditions and slower production.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The project team got together and determined a better way to dry the site and provide adequate access roads thought the worksite. The money that was spent up front was determined to be about 25% of what would have been lost by extending the general conditions.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nThe project our company was working on was impacted by a significant amount of rainfall while the building&rsquo;s foundation and underground construction were beginning. Due to the terms of the contract, all weather delays were excusable but non-compensable. This placed a significant financial burden on the entire project team with regards to extending the general conditions and slower production....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-23',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:34:57','2016-04-11 17:34:57'),(25,'Case 24','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Our company was awarded a project in February 2011. The team worked with the client and the architect to design a facility within a predetermined GMP. An extensive county permit process delayed the project up for approximately 1 year.&nbsp; Due to this delay, market escalation, and funding, the project deemed not feasible to construct.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">As a team, we decided to demobilize from the site and request all subcontractors to cease their work until sufficient funding was available.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nOur company was awarded a project in February 2011. The team worked with the client and the architect to design a facility within a predetermined GMP. An extensive county permit process delayed the project up for approximately 1 year.&nbsp; Due to this delay, market escalation, and funding, the project deemed not feasible to construct....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-24',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:36:15','2016-04-11 17:36:15'),(26,'Case 25','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The demolition contractor working on a project for my company assumed that they were able to sequence their work a certain way. However, this was not clarified during the buy-out process. When the contractor arrived on the site, they found that they were forced to perform their work out of sequence. This was largely due to other trades needing access to certain areas first, logistical constraints, etc. The contractor submitted additional costs for this work despite the fact that there were no actual changes to the contract documents. When these requests were denied, the contractor responded by removing half of their crew from the jobsite.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The demolition contractor&rsquo;s upper management was brought in to review the situation. Together, we were able to sequence their remaining work in a way that was productive for them. With this new plan of action, the contractor agreed to rescind their requests for additional compensation. This plan required additional coordination in the field to maintain the new sequencing plan, but ultimately proved to be worthwhile.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nThe demolition contractor working on a project for my company assumed that they were able to sequence their work a certain way. However, this was not clarified during the buy-out process. When the contractor arrived on the site, they found that they were forced to perform their work out of sequence. This was largely due to other trades needing access to certain areas first, logistical constraints, etc. The contractor submitted additional costs for this work despite the fact that there we...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-25',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:37:11','2016-04-11 17:37:11'),(27,'Case 26','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Approximately one year after installing a glazed curtain wall for a 2 story office building expansion, rust stains started to appear on a number of the glass panels. Upon further review, it was determined that while corrective work was being performed on a number of structural steel connections, the steel erector did not sufficiently protect the glass from welding sparks and slag. We took a panel by panel inventory of each piece of glass with the Owner and determined that 50% of the glass needed to be replaced.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Due to the time between the glass being damaged and the stains developing, there was no absolute proof that the steel erector was responsible for the damage. As a result, my company filed a Builder\'s Risk Claim. This claim paid for the glass to be replaced, less the deductible. While there was no absolute proof that the steel erector damaged the glass, there was enough information to show that no one else could have damaged the glass. My company and the steel erector entered negotiations and eventually reached a settlement that was used to offset the deductible.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nApproximately one year after installing a glazed curtain wall for a 2 story office building expansion, rust stains started to appear on a number of the glass panels. Upon further review, it was determined that while corrective work was being performed on a number of structural steel connections, the steel erector did not sufficiently protect the glass from welding sparks and slag. We took a panel by panel inventory of each piece of glass with the Owner and determined that 50% of the glas...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-26',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:38:58','2016-04-11 17:38:58'),(28,'Case 27','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We had a project in which the surveyor made an error while performing the layout of the elevator pit. This error was not noticed until the pit was poured and the piston holes were drilled and the structural steel was erected. It did not allow enough room for the elevator doors to slide to the side without conflicting with the steel column directly adjacent to the elevator pit.</span></p>','<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We met with the elevator contractor to see what modifications to the elevator car or doors could be made to prevent or minimize the conflict between the doors and the steel column. This required resubmitting the shop drawings for review by the Architect/Engineer.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">In order to make the situation work, we had to modify the structural column by cutting the flanges down and providing 2 (front and back) continuous stiffening plates that were fully welded to support the modified column. This occurred on 3 separate floors.&nbsp; We also had clearance issues which prevented us from utilizing the planned spray fireproofing on this column.&nbsp; We had to get approval from the Authority Having Jurisdication to utilize Intumescent Paint on the modified column.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nWe had a project in which the surveyor made an error while performing the layout of the elevator pit. This error was not noticed until the pit was poured and the piston holes were drilled and the structural steel was erected. It did not allow enough room for the elevator doors to slide to the side without conflicting with the steel column directly adjacent to the elevator pit....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-27',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:40:05','2016-04-11 17:40:05'),(29,'Case 28','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The project we were on was originally scheduled to start in the spring. The project was delayed several months due to the building permitting process. While the project was waiting for the permit, there was an exceptionally rainy summer, a hurricane, and an earthquake. Once the permit had been received and construction had begun, the soil was above the optimum moisture content. This prohibited us from achieving the appropriate level of compaction.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We identified several options to dry the soil. One option was to air dry the soil while the second option was to dry the soil with lime or cement. We ruled out air drying the soil due to time constraints and chose to dry the soil with lime. This option minimized any additional time impacts to the project and allowed construction to progress.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nThe project we were on was originally scheduled to start in the spring. The project was delayed several months due to the building permitting process. While the project was waiting for the permit, there was an exceptionally rainy summer, a hurricane, and an earthquake. Once the permit had been received and construction had begun, the soil was above the optimum moisture content. This prohibited us from achieving the appropriate level of compaction....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-28',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:40:53','2016-04-11 17:40:53'),(30,'Case 29','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We discovered that the steel lintels for a brick facade were not fabricated or installed properly in order to support the brick and stone. The issue proved to be caused by the fact that the structural steel drawings were not coordinated with the architectural details.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We performed a survey of the existing conditions since many of the steel lintels had already been installed. Then, we reached out to several companies that perform welding and steel fabrication in order to get the resources that would correct this problem.&nbsp; In addition, we issued a notice to the owner that stated that we were taking action on this issue that was a result of the contract drawings not being coordinated.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nWe discovered that the steel lintels for a brick facade were not fabricated or installed properly in order to support the brick and stone. The issue proved to be caused by the fact that the structural steel drawings were not coordinated with the architectural details....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-29',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:41:48','2016-04-11 17:41:48'),(31,'Case 30','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The company I work for is currently working on a job where the architect and engineering firms were hired by the owner. The architect recommended the engineering firm despite the fact that the owner had adverse experiences with them in the past. The engineering firm did not design the fire sprinkler system to code and despite this, provided us with stamped drawings to proceed. This was discovered in the middle of the fast paced project and now the schedule has been affected. Additionally, there has been a huge price increase and a significant amount of overtime hours were required to complete the work as close to the original schedule as possible. The engineering firm, our fire protection subcontractor, the owner, and we have had many meetings discussing various topics and the engineering firm is refusing to take the blame for their mistake.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The fire protection subcontractor agreed to do the work included in their original contract. However, once they felt they reached a point where they could not continue until the situation was resolved, they would stop their work. We have been phasing the sprinkler installation on the floors in order to prevent us from falling behind in the schedule. Also, the subcontractor has agreed to increase the amount of installer on the site and to work overtime days. The finished areas of the building will be completed by the original date in the schedule. However, the mechanical and crawl spaces will not be completed on time. There was also a materials shipment delay that affected the start time for a couple of floors. This issue was resolved and we were able to resume work at a reasonable time.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nThe company I work for is currently working on a job where the architect and engineering firms were hired by the owner. The architect recommended the engineering firm despite the fact that the owner had adverse experiences with them in the past. The engineering firm did not design the fire sprinkler system to code and despite this, provided us with stamped drawings to proceed. This was discovered in the middle of the fast paced project and now the schedule has been affected. Additionally...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-30',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:42:43','2016-04-11 17:42:43'),(32,'Case 31','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The drywall subcontractor was repeatedly low on manpower during the height of their work per our schedule which resulted in major mechanical, electrical, and plumbing (MEP) trade delays.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We sent out a 48 hour notice to the subcontractor noting that if they do not supply adequate manpower ASAP we will supplement their labor and in turn they will be responsible for all costs incurred per their contract.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nThe drywall subcontractor was repeatedly low on manpower during the height of their work per our schedule which resulted in major mechanical, electrical, and plumbing (MEP) trade delays....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-31',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:44:06','2016-04-11 17:44:06'),(33,'Case 32','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">On a job site after millwork panels and mirrors had been installed on the walls, with all drawings approved by the architect, it was found that the 17ft x 7ft mirrors were off center by a foot.&nbsp; The architect believed the General Contractor (GC) should have caught the mistake on the drawings, but the GC claimed that they could not be responsible for knowing that the design 