h we were responsible for maintaining the schedule, there were several disputes and issues getting timely deliverables from the subcontractors who were not contracted through our company....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-34',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:47:00','2016-04-11 17:47:00'),(36,'Case 35','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">My company was building a new store for a high profile client on an ivy league campus. This involved tearing down half of the existing book store and building a new building in its place. The schedule was a compressed schedule with little room for delays. The structural steel was delayed by 2 months and we were left building an 8,000 square foot store that included complicated interior steel finishes, 200,000lbs of exterior stone cladding and large glass store front panels in 7 weeks from initial steel delivery to store opening day.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We worked with all of the subcontractors to coordinate a very busy site that involved every trade working in conjunction to construct the building in a safe manner, and worked to keep the quality to the high standard. It was a very complicated process.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nMy company was building a new store for a high profile client on an ivy league campus. This involved tearing down half of the existing book store and building a new building in its place. The schedule was a compressed schedule with little room for delays. The structural steel was delayed by 2 months and we were left building an 8,000 square foot store that included complicated interior steel finishes, 200,000lbs of exterior stone cladding and large glass store front panels in 7 weeks fro...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-35',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:48:18','2016-04-11 17:48:18'),(37,'Case 36','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We were on a project in North Carolina and we had a group of subcontractors that refused to work next to people of a different race.&nbsp; The schedule was at risk and it created problem on site.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We had called the managers of each company and had them address the issue internally.&nbsp; The work was completed on time.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nWe were on a project in North Carolina and we had a group of subcontractors that refused to work next to people of a different race.&nbsp; The schedule was at risk and it created problem on site....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-36',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:57:25','2016-04-11 17:57:25'),(38,'Case 37','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The company I work for was told that a specific project was ours and to submit pricing for it. There was a start and completion date all set. While pricing the project, it was brought to our attention that there were two other GC\'s bidding against us. Once pricing was submitted, the project was put on hold.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We proceeded bidding as if we were toe only GC pricing this project. We reached out to even more subcontractors to get more numbers in order to try to get a better overall price. We submitted our pricing and then were told that the project was on hold after repricing based on addendums that came out. We now are awaiting to hear back as to what the status of this project is.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nThe company I work for was told that a specific project was ours and to submit pricing for it. There was a start and completion date all set. While pricing the project, it was brought to our attention that there were two other GC\'s bidding against us. Once pricing was submitted, the project was put on hold....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-37',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:58:04','2016-04-11 17:58:04'),(39,'Case 38','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We were heading towards the end of construction on stadium seating.&nbsp; Per code the rails can be as low as 26\" high, yet OSHA&nbsp; regulations state that guard rails need to be a minimum of 42\".&nbsp; We had already removed the temporary guard rails and installed the final rails, which were at 32\".&nbsp; While in the process of&nbsp; painting and putting the finishing touches on the bleacher seating, we were issued a stop work order by our safety department because we were technically still in construction.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The workers were required to put on harness and tie off while working the entire seating area.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nWe were heading towards the end of construction on stadium seating.&nbsp; Per code the rails can be as low as 26\" high, yet OSHA&nbsp; regulations state that guard rails need to be a minimum of 42\".&nbsp; We had already removed the temporary guard rails and installed the final rails, which were at 32\".&nbsp; While in the process of&nbsp; painting and putting the finishing touches on the bleacher seating, we were issued a stop work order by our safety department because we were technicall...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-38',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:58:48','2016-04-11 17:58:48'),(40,'Case 39','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">A Fire Marshal walked the project during final inspections and asked for additional exits devices.&nbsp; He had not previously made this request either during the plan review or during earlier inspections.&nbsp; The devices are above and beyond those required by the building and fire codes.&nbsp; He&nbsp; would not allow the client to occupy the project with the excess work being completed.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We reviewed the situation with the client, evaluating the options that were in front of the team.&nbsp; Option A was to do the work requested by the inspector and Option B was to appeal his decision.&nbsp; The appeal would require first an appeal to the local fire department and then to the state board.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nA Fire Marshal walked the project during final inspections and asked for additional exits devices.&nbsp; He had not previously made this request either during the plan review or during earlier inspections.&nbsp; The devices are above and beyond those required by the building and fire codes.&nbsp; He&nbsp; would not allow the client to occupy the project with the excess work being completed....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-39',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 17:59:33','2016-04-11 17:59:33'),(41,'Case 40','<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Our company was awarded a high-profile historic preservation project in the heart of Boston and work was to begin in 2006. The total project duration was to be roughly one year but only a few months into the project the owner ran out of money. The work was put on hold until further notice with the owner in debt to our company a substantial amount of money for work in place.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">In 2009 the owner was granted money from the government to complete the project. It was enough money to cover the cost of the work not yet in place but not enough to cover the debt the owner was already in for work already performed.</span></p>','<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Due to the high profile nature of the job and also understanding that if we went forward with the project the owner would have a much better chance of gathering money from donors, we decided to go forward with the project.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We set up a payment plan with the owner to pay off the old debt in quarterly payments. We treated the remainder of the work as a separate job altogether and were paid our standard monthly payments.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We finished the job and were paid in full for the new work but to the best of my knowledge the owner is still paying off the old debt.</span></p>','','Our company was awarded a high-profile historic preservation project in the heart of Boston and work was to begin in 2006. The total project duration was to be roughly one year but only a few months into the project the owner ran out of money. The work was put on hold until further notice with the owner in debt to our company a substantial amount of money for work in place.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nIn 2009 the owner was granted money from the government to complete the project. It was enough money to cover the ...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-40',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 18:00:30','2016-04-11 18:00:30'),(42,'Case 41','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">During a bid, the drawings showed existing structural framing detail for the storefront system. After the job was awarded, the architect went to survey the field and noticed there was no existing structure that could hold the proposed storefront framing in place. The architect told us that we would have to include to pay for the design of the structural framing and include the material and labor needed.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We responded to the client and architect that it was shown in the drawings as an existing condition and after the contract was signed, we agreed to do all the work shown in the drawings. The result was a negotiation to issue a change order to cover the costs instead of paying for it directly out of our pocket.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nDuring a bid, the drawings showed existing structural framing detail for the storefront system. After the job was awarded, the architect went to survey the field and noticed there was no existing structure that could hold the proposed storefront framing in place. The architect told us that we would have to include to pay for the design of the structural framing and include the material and labor needed....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-41',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 18:02:23','2016-04-11 18:02:23'),(43,'Case 42','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The company that I was involved in laid out the exact location of a proposed foundation. When the foundation was poured and forms stripped, we were required to locate the exact corners of the foundation to prepare a certified foundation plan. This is used to confirm you meet zoning set back issues. Upon locating the foundation, we determined that the foundation was too close to the sideline and did not meet zoning setback regulations.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">Once we determined that the foundation was incorrectly laid out too close to the sidelines and did not conform to zoning, we informed the owner. To solve the problem, it was decided to cut the foundation back about two feet, and repour the wall. Once this was completed, the new wall met zoning requirements.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nThe company that I was involved in laid out the exact location of a proposed foundation. When the foundation was poured and forms stripped, we were required to locate the exact corners of the foundation to prepare a certified foundation plan. This is used to confirm you meet zoning set back issues. Upon locating the foundation, we determined that the foundation was too close to the sideline and did not meet zoning setback regulations....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-42',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 18:03:07','2016-04-11 18:03:07'),(44,'Case 43','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We were awarded a job about to start.&nbsp; The previous Project Manager (PM) did not have everything (contracts, etc...) well documented and left the company before the job started, and thus a lot of deals were made verbally without written documentation.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">We negotiated the deals with the documentation that we did have and worked to ensure moving forward that work was properly scoped out and documented.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nWe were awarded a job about to start.&nbsp; The previous Project Manager (PM) did not have everything (contracts, etc...) well documented and left the company before the job started, and thus a lot of deals were made verbally without written documentation....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-43',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 18:03:57','2016-04-11 18:03:57'),(45,'Case 44','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">My former company was doing a sewer interceptor project in Delaware and came across some unforeseen conditions. What was unforeseen was Brandywine Blue Granite, the second hardest rock known to man. The soil borings never mentioned anything about competent rock on the job and the worst part was that we could not blast due to the vicinity of the high speed rail line owned by Amtrak. On top of that the old line was falling apart and was only 6\' away from the centerline of the new pipeline. So even if we could blast we would have had to set up temporary bypass pumping for a daily flow of 32 million gallons. To make matters even worse, the owner (New Castle County of Delaware), had put a price in the bid to remove competent rock and my company did not bury money to cover the cost to remove the rock. Talk about being stuck between a hard place and a rock.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">In order to get through this rock our crews spent 5 months using hydraulic drill and splitters to slowly chip away at the rock face. We bought numerous hammer bits for the hydraulic hammer attached to the excavator, looked for and bought hundreds of harder drilling bits, used chemicals that would rapidly expand and split the rock, and did anything we could to get through that rock faster. In the end it just took sheer manpower and time to get through that 200\' stretch, but to make matters worse the owner refused to pay us and the company had to go to litigation to recover over a million dollars in losses due to this unforeseen condition.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nMy former company was doing a sewer interceptor project in Delaware and came across some unforeseen conditions. What was unforeseen was Brandywine Blue Granite, the second hardest rock known to man. The soil borings never mentioned anything about competent rock on the job and the worst part was that we could not blast due to the vicinity of the high speed rail line owned by Amtrak. On top of that the old line was falling apart and was only 6\' away from the centerline of the new pipeline....','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-44',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 18:04:50','2016-04-11 18:04:50'),(46,'Case 45','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The company I last worked for received quotes from multiple subcontractors in order to bid on a job as a General Contractor (GC)/ Construction Manager (CM).&nbsp; One of the quotes for millwork was a very low price compared to everyone else.&nbsp; We (estimating) called and told the millwork subcontractor that they probably have a bad number.&nbsp; Our VP also called the sub and asked that they pull their bid from us as well as any other GC/CMs that they may have submitted a bid to for the same job.&nbsp; They were adamant that they had all the scope and were not going to pull their quote.&nbsp; We ended up using their bid to remain competitive and were the low bidder. However during the buyout, the same millwork sub raised their price by $1,000,000. The project was a lump sum bid, so we could not go back to the owner for more money.&nbsp; The project was about $55,000,000 in total.</span></p>','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"p1\"><span class=\"s1\">The increase in price made the quote higher than other millwork subs. We had to plan our buyout extremely carefully and specifically looked at breaking certain scopes in smaller packages.&nbsp; The overall scope of work for the millwork was in the $3,000,000 range, and initially smaller subcontractors were not able to bid, as it was more than they could handle. By making smaller packages smaller subs were allowed to get involved.&nbsp; We also considered the idea of buying the casework portion directly from manufacturers and getting an installation price from the subs, which would allow us to cut out the markup and also go to just the installers who originally did not provide a quote as it was all inclusive &amp; too large.</span></p>','','&nbsp;\r\nThe company I last worked for received quotes from multiple subcontractors in order to bid on a job as a General Contractor (GC)/ Construction Manager (CM).&nbsp; One of the quotes for millwork was a very low price compared to everyone else.&nbsp; We (estimating) called and told the millwork subcontractor that they probably have a bad number.&nbsp; Our VP also called the sub and asked that they pull their bid from us as well as any other GC/CMs that they may have submitted a bid to for t...','no','no',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'case-45',1,1,NULL,'2016-04-11 18:05:41','2016-04-11 18:05:41');
